FLY
  Fly planes to a new airfield or on a transport mission.

SYNTAX
  fly <plane-spec> <target-x,y>

DESCRIPTION
  Moves planes from their current airfield to another location.
  Unlike 'bomb', this is used for repositioning, dropping
  paratroopers, or air transport of commodities.

  <plane-spec>  - plane uid ("5"), range ("0-5"), comma list ("2,14"),
                  "*" for all owned planes, "~" for planes with no
                  wing assigned, or a single letter naming a wing
                  (see 'info wingadd' to group planes into a wing)

  The destination must be within the plane's range.
  Planes consume fuel (petrol) during flight.

  Planes must land at a friendly airfield (type '*') at >=40% eff,
  unless they are dropped as paratroopers — OR aboard a friendly
  carrier ship sitting at the destination.  Carriers are tried first:
  if one is there, has room, and is >=50% efficient, the plane lands
  aboard it instead of the sector (works even over open sea, as long
  as a carrier is present).  A plane that fits no carrier falls back
  to the sector rule above; one that fits neither has nowhere to land
  and crashes.  See 'info load' for how planes get *onto* a carrier or
  missile sub in the first place, and which plane types qualify.

  Planes require at least 40% efficiency to fly.

  v1 gap: no interactive "which carrier?" choice if several are
  present at the destination — eligible carriers are filled in uid
  order.

EXAMPLE
  fly * 4,2                 rebase all planes to airfield at 4,2
  fly 0 -6,0                move plane 0 to the western airfield
  fly 5 -2,-6               fly plane 5 to wherever your carrier is —
                            it lands aboard if there's room

SEE ALSO
  bomb  wingadd  launch  recon  load  mission  build  navigate
